/16/1366102983343/COURTS-Extradition-1-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Elizabeth Cook/PA") (media:description nil "Court sketch of Haroon Aswat 31, during a 2006 extradition hearing. Photograph: Elizabeth Cook/PA")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/16/1366102989147/COURTS-Extradition-1-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Elizabeth Cook/PA") (media:description nil "Court sketch of Haroon Aswat during a extradition hearing in 2006. Photograph: Elizabeth Cook/PA"))) (item nil (title nil "Honduran journalist survives murder attempt") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/greenslade/2013/apr/16/journalist-safety-honduras") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/94291?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Ajournalist-safety-honduras%3A1894409&ch=Media&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Media%2CJournalist+safety%2CHonduras+%28News%29%2CAmericas+%28News%29%2CWorld+news%2CHuman+rights%2CPress+freedom+%28Media%29&c5=Press+Media%2CUnclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CMedia+Weekly&c6=Roy+Greenslade&c7=2013%2F04%2F16+07%3A02&c8=1894409&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost%2CNews&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=Greenslade+blog&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Honduran+journalist+survives+murder+attempt&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FMedia%2Fblog%2FGreenslade\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p>A shot was fired at Honduran television journalist Fidelina Sandoval as she was entering the Globo TV station last Monday (8 April) in what looks to have been an attempted murder.</p><p>She told colleagues that a passenger in grey pick-up truck fired at her but missed and she scrambled to safety by running towards two guards and a taxi driver. </p><p>The incident followed four days after she reported receiving two strange anonymous calls  after she broadcast about the need for police reforms related to the killings of members of a peasant movement.</p><p>Since 2009, it is claimed that more than 30 people, including several journalists, have been killed for exercising their right to freedom of expression in Honduras. </p><p><em>Sources:</em> <a href=\"http://www.resistenciahonduras.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=5540:unknown-men-attempt-to-murder-tv-globo-journalist-fidelina-sandoval-&catid=103:human-rights&Itemid=352\">Resistencia Honduras</a>/<a href=\"http://protectionline.org/2013/04/11/honduras-shots-fired-at-human-rights-defender-and-journalist-ms-fidelina-sandoval-front-line/\">Protection Line</a></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/journalist-safety\">Journalist safety</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/honduras\">Honduras</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/americas\">Americas</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/human-rights\">Human rights</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/press-freedom\">Press freedom</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/roygreenslade\">Roy Greenslade</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Media") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Journalist safety") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Honduras") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Americas") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law")) "Human rights") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Press freedom") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Tue, 16 Apr 2013 06:00:00 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/greenslade/2013/apr/16/journalist-safety-honduras") (dc:creator nil "Roy Greenslade") (dc:subject nil "Media") (dc:date nil "2013-04-16T06:02:25Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407252318")) (item nil (title nil "Complexity of parliamentary legislation 'undermining the rule of law'") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/2013/apr/16/parliamentary-legislation-too-complex-report") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/35355?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aparliamentary-legislation-too-complex-report%3A1894157&ch=Law&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Law%2CHouse+of+Commons%2CHouse+of+Lords&c5=Not+commercially+useful&c6=Owen+Bowcott&c7=2013%2F04%2F16+12%3A01&c8=1894157&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Complexity+of+parliamentary+legislation+%27undermining+the+rule+of+law%27&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FLaw%2FHouse+of+Commons\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Cabinet Office chief calls for laws to be simplified in digital age so that lay citizens are not baffled when they access them</p><p>Parliamentary legislation is excessively complex and its confusions undermine the rule of law, according to the official in charge of drafting government statutes.</p><p>In a report published on Tuesday, Richard Heaton, permanent secretary at the Cabinet Office, calls for regulations to be made easier to understand so that non-specialists can navigate their way through the maze of regulations.</p><p>Judges and legal academics, his report suggests, may be called in to advise on how legislation might be improved at an earlier stage.</p><p>\"The digital age has made it easier for people to find the law of the land, but once they have found it, they may be baffled,\" Heaton says in the study, When Laws Become Too Complex. \"The law is regarded by its users as intricate and intimidating.\"</p><p>In his post of first parliamentary counsel, Heaton is also in charge of the office established in 1869 to improve the drafting of government bills.</p><p>\"The volume of legislation, its piecemeal structure, its level of detail and frequent amendments, and the interaction with common law and European law, mean that even professional users can find law complex, hard to understand and difficult to comply with,\" he says.</p><p>\"Excessive complexity hinders economic activity, creating burdens for individuals, businesses and communities. It obstructs good government. It undermines the rule of law.\"</p><p>Heaton's report coincides with the launch of a \"good law initiative\" aimed at simplifying legislation, particularly the way it is presented through the government website <a href=\"http://www.legislation.gov.uk/\" title=\"\">legislation.gov.uk</a>.</p><p>One of the initiative's ambitions is to \"talk to the judges who authoritatively interpret the law and to the universities which teach it, to avoid confusion and facilitate interpretation\".</p><p>It also plans to \"ensure that legislation is as accessible as possible, and consider what more can be done to improve readability\".</p><p>The scheme is backed by Andrew Lansley, the leader of the House of Commons, who said: \"As MP and minister, I am well aware of how challenging it is to legislate in a way which effectively, simply and consistently promotes the interests of the people we serve, without creating delay or uncertainty.\"</p><p>Parliamentary drafting has evolved a more comprehensible form of English since the 19th century but interpreting the law remains an exercise almost exclusively undertaken by experienced lawyers.</p><p>The report records that the average number of government bills in a typical parliamentary session is currently between 35 and 50 depending on the length of the session. Between 1983 and 2009 parliament approved more than 100 criminal justice bills and more than 4,000 new criminal offences were created.</p><p>The amount of so-called \"delegated legislation\", involving statutory instruments, has increased significantly in recent decades from around 2,000 a year in the 1980s to around double that number in 2006.</p><p>Frustration at the intricacy and entanglements of the statute book are not new. The report quotes Edward VI (1537-1553) as lamenting: \"I wish that the superfluous and tedious statutes were brought into one sum together, and made more plain and short.\"</p><p>There are more than a million words of law governing immigration controls, the good law project has discovered, far more than the number of words written by Shakespeare. Such complexity may, understandably, baffle even UK Border Agency officials.</p><p>Another confusing tradition is that bills going through parliament refer to \"clauses\", but when they become acts they become \"sections\".</p><p>The initiative is intended to complement the government's campaign against red tape and bureaucracy. \"Users perceive complying with legislation to be onerous and the law as being extremely difficult to navigate,\" the report says. \"In particular, in the areas of planning and environmental applications, procedural bureaucracy is perceived to be a problem for businesses.\"</p><p>It adds: \"Most European countries have set up processes to simplify national legislation and established departments dedicated entirely to better regulation and reform of the law.\"</p><p>Cutting down on the number of protracted appeals up through the hierarchy of the courts to ascertain the precise meaning of some obscure legislative clause is one aspiration of the project.</p><p>Computer-assisted analysis of statutes could help untangle the more impenetrable recesses of the law, the report suggests. \"Computational legal studies emerged over a decade ago in the US and are based on the premise that legislation, as any other sets of complex and intertwined information, can be analysed and organised according to mathematical models.</p><p>\"If we look at statutes as data, then legislation can be formalised (and visualised) as a mathematical object, a hierarchically organised structure containing language and explicit interdependence between provisions.\"</p><p>The prospect of judges peering over their computer terminals at the plaintiff may not be so distant.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/houseofcommons\">House of Commons</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/lords\">House of Lords</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/owenbowcott\">Owen Bowcott</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law")) "Law") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "House of Commons") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "House of Lords") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Mon, 15 Apr 2013 23:01:02 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/2013/apr/16/parliamentary-legislation-too-complex-report") (dc:creator nil "Owen Bowcott") (dc:subject nil "Law") (dc:date nil "2013-04-15T23:06:12Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407222969") (media:keywords nil "Law, House of Commons, House of Lords") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/15/1366036289371/Houses-of-Parliament-on-a-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Andrew Winning/Reuters") (media:description nil "Clarity obscured: the law made in Westminster 'is regarded by its users as intricate and intimidating', according to Richard Heaton. Photograph: Andrew Winning/Reuters")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/15/1366036295287/Houses-of-Parliament-on-a-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Andrew Winning/Reuters") (media:description nil "Clarity obscured: the law made in Westminster 'is regarded by its users as intricate and intimidating', according to Richard Heaton. Photograph: Andrew Winning/Reuters"))) (item nil (title nil "Commerzbank 'victimised' employee over discrimination case, tribunal rules") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/2013/apr/15/commerzbank-employment-tribunal") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/37398?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Acommerzbank-employment-tribunal%3A1894392&ch=Money&c3=Guardian&c4=Employment+tribunals%2CBusiness%2CDeutsche+Bank%2CBanking+%28Business+sector%29%2CEuropean+banks+%28business%29%2CWorld+news%2CFinancial+sector+%28business%29%2CEurope+%28News%29%2CWork+and+careers%2CMoney%2CEmployment+law%2CLaw&c5=Personal+Finance%2CUnclassified%2CBusiness+Markets%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CInvestments+%26+Savings&c6=Rupert+Neate&c7=2013%2F04%2F15+09%3A36&c8=1894392&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Commerzbank+%27victimised%27+employee+over+discrimination+case%2C+tribunal+rules&c66=Money&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FMoney%2FMoney%2FEmployment+tribunals\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Latifa Bouabdillah was sacked by Commerzbank for breach of trust but tribunal says this was 'both offensive and unfair'</p><p>A City banker was \"victimised\" by her bank after it discovered she was suing her former employer for sexual discrimination, a tribunal has ruled. Latifa Bouabdillah was sacked by Commerzbank after less than a month when her boss heard she was suing her former employer, Deutsche Bank, for more than £1m in damages for sexual discrimination.</p><p>An employment tribunal ruled on Monday that Commerzbank had \"victimised [Bouabdillah] for having brought sex discrimination proceedings against her former employer and subjected her to the detrimental dismissal\".</p><p>But it rejected the sexual discrimination charge and the bank said it was \"considering its legal options with regards to the other part of the claim\".</p><p>A \"remedy hearing\" is scheduled for September, at which Bouabdillah will claim for £13m in damages.</p><p>The tribunal said Commerzbank had an \"immediate and emotional response\" to discovering that Bouabdillah was suing her former employer for sex discrimination. \"We find they were uncomfortable with this and decided not to continue with the relationship because this was not the sort of person they wanted to employ,\" the tribunal said in its judgment.</p><p>She resigned as a vice-president at Deutsche Bank in 2011 and launched a lawsuit claiming her male colleagues were promoted ahead of her and received three times the bonuses that she did.</p><p>Bouabdillah was sacked by Commerzbank on 11 June 2012 – six days after her case against Deutsche Bank became public, following press coverage. It was less than a month after she had started work at Commerzbank.</p><p>Commerzbank had claimed that her case against Deutsche Bank had put the reputation of her new employer \"at risk\" and had broken the bank's trust.</p><p>Her boss, Guy Middleton, had <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/2013/mar/19/banker-sacked-sex-bias-case\" title=\"\">told the tribunal</a>that he was suspicious about why she had left Deutsche Bank and repeatedly asked her recruitment consultant, but was assured it was because she wanted to move to a smaller team.</p><p>\"I was initially unsure whether Latifa should remain in the team as I initially thought that the trust between her and the team might be recoverable,\" Middleton, head of Commerzbank's sales and trading at its exotic vanilla funds team, told the tribunal. \"But as time went on I felt that she had made a conscious and considered decision to withhold information, which made me feel that she could no longer be trusted.\"</p><p>The tribunal ruled that Commerzbank had been \"both offensive and unfair\" in claiming that Bouabdillah should have informed them of her sexual discrimination case against Deutsche Bank in the same way that bankers are required to disclose legal action against themselves.</p><p>The judgement ruled that Bouabdillah had not misled Commerzbank. \"When asked direct questions she gave direct answers,\" it said. \"They may not have been entirely full answers but that is not a matter of misleading or being dishonest … The failure to answer questions that were not asked does not in our view amount to a lack of honesty or trust.\"</p><p>It added: \"There is no evidence that the claimant [Bouabdillah] at any stage neglected her duties to the bank and there is no suggestion that she acted unprofessionally in any of her dealings albeit she had not been at the bank very long.\"</p><p>A Commerzbank spokesman said: \" [She] was dismissed for a breach of trust and confidence after having failed adequately to disclose the true reasons for leaving her former employer. She, like many employees of Commerzbank, was in a role of significant trust and responsibility. Honesty and trustworthiness are paramount to the bank and its customers.</p><p>\"We are committed to ensuring a positive, motivating and rewarding working environment that enables staff to reach their full potential with systems of training and support and, unusually for businesses of its kind, a policy of balancing individual needs with those of the bank.\"</p><p>The sexual discrimination case against Deutsche Bank was settled out of court and the terms have not been disclosed.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/employment-tribunals\">Employment tribunals</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/deutschebank\">Deutsche Bank</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/banking\">Banking</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/europeanbanks\">European banks</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/financial-sector\">Financial sector</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/europe-news\">Europe</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/work-and-careers\">Work & careers</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/employment-law\">Employment law</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/rupertneate\">Rupert Neate</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/money")) "Employment tribunals") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Business") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Deutsche Bank")