ank had an 'immediate, emotional response', the tribunal said, to discovering that Latifa Bouabdillah was suing her former employer.  Photograph: Sean Gallup/Getty"))) (item nil (title nil "Battle to save key equality legislation") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/2013/apr/15/battle-key-equality-legislation") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/75558?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Abattle-key-equality-legislation%3A1894296&ch=Law&c3=Guardian&c4=Equality+Act+2010%2CEquality+%28Society%29%2CSociety%2CLaw%2CEquality+and+Human+Rights+Commission+%28EHRC%29&c5=Society+Weekly%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CCommunities+Society&c6=&c7=2013%2F04%2F15+09%3A00&c8=1894296&c9=Article&c10=Letter&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Battle+to+save+key+equality+legislation&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FLaw%2FEquality+Act+2010\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p>We write to highlight&nbsp;how important it is to retain <a href=\"http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2010/15/contents\" title=\"\">section 3 of the Equality Act</a>. It is of critical importance that the <a href=\"http://www.equalityhumanrights.com/advice-and-guidance/public-sector-equality-duty/faqs-on-the-equality-duty/\" title=\"\">general equality duty</a> – which the House of Lords voted, with a significant majority, to retain on 4 March – is not overturned or repealed during the last stage of the <a href=\"http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2012-13/enterpriseandregulatoryreform.html\" title=\"\">enterprise and regulatory reform bill</a> in the Commons today, 16 April.</p><p>The government has said that the objective of its reforms to the Equality and Human Rights Commission is to focus on the areas where it can add value because of its unique role and functions. It has failed to explain how the commission, which has already been&nbsp;significantly slimmed down, with fewer powers at its disposal, can be more effective than one that retains the role and powers given by parliament&nbsp;only six&nbsp;years ago.</p><p>The Liberal Democrats, along with all parties at the time, supported a strong general duty. We are now told by the government that this is \"too wide-ranging, and creates unrealistic expectations\". We are also told that it would make \"little difference\" to the work of the commission. Then why bother to remove it?</p><p>Liberal Democrats&nbsp;are committed to a fair and equal society, and for this reason we strongly believe it is important that all Lib Dem MPs support the amendment voted on in the House of Lords to stop the repeal of this fundamental equality law.</p><p>We also believe that the government has a choice between a strong independent body that is committed to promoting and safeguarding our values, independent of the government of the day – of whichever colour – or we go for the option of a watered-down, less independent, weaker institution, which in time would be rendered merely an enforcement agency or regulator without the vision and underpinning that is so important.</p><p>The general equality duty is a result of hard-fought rights following the tragedy of the Stephen Lawrence case, and it is such an important part of the legacy of the fight for justice that Doreen Lawrence wrote to the prime minister urging&nbsp;that it is retained. We hope that&nbsp;he&nbsp;and the government will listen to her&nbsp;plea. Indeed, we hope that they will also heed the respondents to the government's own consultation on the issue, which said by a ratio of 6:1 that the general equality duty should not be&nbsp;repealed.<br /><strong>Meral Hussein-Ece</strong><br /><strong>Sal Brinton</strong><br /><em>Liberal Democrats, House of Lords</em></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/equality-act-2010\">Equality Act 2010</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/equality\"