e shared by a number of other countries including the US. The chancellor has also expressed his concerns to the German finance minister Wolfgang Schäuble.</p><p>Britain's objections concern the scope of the tax. Treasury sources said under the current plans it would be levied on a trade in a euro-denominated financial instrument conducted in Singapore by two American banks, for instance.</p><p>The City has also sought clarification on how the levy would affect euro trades completed in London between banks from countries not in the scheme, and from UK subsidiaries of banks in participating countries.</p><p>Osborne believes the tax will damage an already weak eurozone economy and be costly for savers and pensioners because the costs will be passed on.</p><p>It is thought the ECJ will take up to two years to consider the UK's case, but the Treasury believes the legislative process to put the tax into force will take longer. Britain believes its objections can be met while the legislation is being passed and sees the court case as an insurance policy.</p><p>Supporters of the financial transaction tax criticised Osborne's decision. Owen Tudor, spokesman for the <a href=\"http://robinhoodtax.org.uk/\" title=\"\">Robin Hood Tax campaign</a>, said: \"This isn't about defending British interests against Europe – it's about defending one rather rich square mile against the wishes of people in Britain and across Europe.</p><p>\"Not content with letting our banks off scot-free, Osborne now wants to prevent European countries from making their financial sectors pay to repair the damage caused by the crisis.</p><p>\"Resorting to lawyers is the last refuge of a chancellor who has lost the argument.</p><p>\"Not only is this morally wrong, it is breathtakingly hypocritical – the UK's own £3bn stamp duty on shares is collected wherever UK shares are traded and regardless of who is trading them.\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/european-court-of-justice\">Court of justice of the European Union</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/european-commission\">European commission</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/eu\">European Union</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/europe-news\">Europe</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/georgeosborne\">George Osborne</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/tobin-tax\">Tobin tax</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/economics\">Economics</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/banking\">Banking</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/financial-crisis\">Financial crisis</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/financial-sector\">Financial sector</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/larryelliott\">Larry Elliott</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law")) "Court of justice of the European Union") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law")) "Law") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "European commission") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "European Union") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Europe") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "George Osborne") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "Politics") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Tobin tax") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Economics") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Banking") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Financial crisis") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Financial sector") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Business") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 17:01:03 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/2013/apr/19/uk-legal-challenge-financial-transaction-tax") (dc:creator nil "Larry Elliott") (dc:subject nil "Law") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T17:01:03Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407535617") (media:keywords nil "Court of justice of the European Union, Law, European commission, European Union, Europe, World news, George Osborne, Politics, Tobin tax, Economics, Banking, Financial crisis, Financial sector, Business") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/cartoons/2013/4/19/1366390643118/U.S.-Treasury-Secretary-J-004.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Yuri Gripas/Reuters") (media:description nil "George Osborne with Jack Lew, the US treasury secretary, in Washington. Photograph: Yuri Gripas/Reuters")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/cartoons/2013/4/19/1366390649461/U.S.-Treasury-Secretary-J-009.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Yuri Gripas/Reuters") (media:description nil "George Osborne with Jack Lew, the US treasury secretary, in Washington. Photograph: Yuri Gripas/Reuters")))) ("The midwife who told the truth in the Savita Halappanavar abortion case | Emer O'Toole" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/62917?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Asavita-halappanavar-abortion-midwife%3A1896735&ch=Comment+is+free&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Abortion+%28News%29%2CIreland+%28News%29%2CCatholicism+%28News%29%2CHealth+%28Society%29%2CWomen+and+women%27s+interests%2CWorld+news%2CEurope+%28News%29%2CReligion+%28News%29%2CLaw&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CWomen%2CHealth+Society&c6=Emer+O%27Toole&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+07%3A15&c8=1896735&c9=Blog&c10=Comment&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=Comment+is+free&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=The+midwife+who+told+the+truth+in+the+Savita+Halappanavar+abortion+case&c66=Comment+is+free&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FComment+is+free%2FComment+is+free%2Fblog%2FComment+is+free\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Ann Maria Burke acknowledged the logic behind denying an abortion to Halappanavar: Ireland is a Catholic country</p><p>The inquest into Savita Halappanavar's death has unanimously delivered its verdict: her death was <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/savita-halappanavar-medical-misadventure-inquest\" title=\"\">due to medical misadventure</a>. Halappanavar died after being denied an emergency termination in October and her case has since been at the centre of Ireland's abortion wars. The inquest jury strongly endorsed the nine recommendations of the coroner, Ciaran MacLoughlin, including a suggestion that the Irish Medical Council lay out exactly when a doctor can intervene to save the life of a mother in similar circumstances.</p><p>The significance of this will only be known when the medical council delivers its guidelines. Abortion in Ireland is permitted where there is a real and substantial threat to the life of the mother. If the medical council agrees that termination is permitted whenever a foetal membrane ruptures, then there is an implication that a small risk to the life of the mother trumps the right to life of the foetus. Not all women with ruptured membranes develop sepsis, and, to the best of my understanding, most sepsis is treatable through antibiotics. It would, therefore, be difficult to categorise ruptured membranes as a substantial risk to life.</p><p>If the medical council agrees that termination is permitted where the foetus is unviable, then this may open the door to termination for fatal foetal abnormality, currently illegal in the Republic. But all this is simply speculation – the medical council is a conservative beast: it could equally provide guidelines that support the actions of Halappanavar's medical team, who moved to terminate only when her sepsis was genuinely life-threatening.</p><p>Halappanavar's death made people who usually ignore the fact that Ireland is a little dot of backwardness in a sea of progressive reproductive values sit up and take note. She did not die for want of a termination in a developing country, but in 21st-century western Europe. Increasingly cosmopolitan, and, in spite of the crash, no longer the EU's poor and pitiable ward, it's easy to forget that Ireland is a very conservative country compared with its European counterparts. As I <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/belief/2013/mar/15/abortion-ireland-opus-dei-catholic\" title=\"\">have argued before</a>, the separation of church and state in Ireland is an incomplete project at best.</p><p>At the inquest, Halappanavar's consultant, Dr Katherine Astbury, said that she met her patient's request for an abortion with the explanation that a poor foetal prognosis does not provide legal grounds for termination in the Republic. It must seem incomprehensible to people outside Ireland that when Halappanavar asked for a termination knowing that her pregnancy could not survive she was denied one because of the presence of a foetal heartbeat. In Ireland, however, women told that they are carrying live foetuses with fatal abnormalities routinely go to the UK to abort rather than wait weeks for their pregnancy to die, all the while growing bigger and trying to answer cheerful questions about the new baby without breaking into tears.</p><p>What's important to note here is that Halappanavar – a foreign national and a medical professional – felt it within her right to ask for a termination. Would an Irishwoman, brought up in a culture in which abortion is a dirty word and a shameful deed – and especially a less educated or differently educated Irishwoman – even have asked? Sometimes it takes an outside element to show how utterly messed up the system is.</p><p>One of the reasons that Halappanavar's death became an international news story was her husband Praveen's insistence that hospital staff told his wife that she couldn't have a termination because Ireland is a Catholic country. During the inquest, the midwife Ann Maria Burke came forward to <a href=\"http://www.irishtimes.com/news/ann-maria-burke-says-remark-was-intended-to-be-broad-and-explanatory-1.1356387\" title=\"\">apologetically explain that she was the source of this remark</a>. She said that she had only wanted to throw light on Irish culture for Halappanavar, explaining: \"It was the law of the land and there were two referendums where the Catholic church was pressing the buttons.\" From reportage, it looks as though she was all but slapped on the wrist by the coroner, who told her that Irish public hospitals do not follow any religious tenet or dogma.</p><p>Burke deserves praise, not sanction, for telling Halappanavar the truth as to why she couldn't have a termination. Where Astbury defends her medical practice through reference to law, and MacLoughlin places Irish hospitals above religious dogma, Burke alone acknowledges the logic behind the legality. The only possible logic for denying Halappanavar the treatment she would have received in other developed countries is Catholic logic.</p><p>The evidence given at the inquest shows unequivocally that Halappanavar would have received different treatment in a different jurisdiction. Astbury admitted as much, and expert witness Dr Peter Boylan has said Halappanavar would most likely be alive if she'd been given a termination, as she requested, within two days of admission to hospital.</p><p>The inquest into Halappanavar's death has delivered its verdict on what would have been her fifth wedding anniversary. I inject this element of humanity into my article not to tug on heartstrings for a pro-choice cause, but to remind us that, for all that Halappanavar's death has come to symbolise in Ireland, hers is a human story and a human tragedy. Praveen Halappanavar <a href=\"http://www.irishtimes.com/news/husband-objects-to-inquiry-members-1.554117\" title=\"\">has said</a>: \"The law has to change. Maybe Savita was born to change the law here.\" Maybe she was, but I wish that the Irish people could have done that work without her, and I wish Savita Halappanavar were celebrating her anniversary with her husband tonight.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/abortion\">Abortion</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/ireland\">Ireland</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/catholicism\">Catholicism</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/health\">Health</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/women\">Women</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/europe-news\">Europe</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/religion\">Religion</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/emer-o-toole\">Emer O'Toole</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2013/apr/19/savita-halappanavar-abortion-midwife" (20849 35237) old 6 nil nil ((title nil "The midwife who told the truth in the Savita Halappanavar abortion case | Emer O'Toole") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2013/apr/19/savita-halappanavar-abortion-midwife") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/62917?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Asavita-halappanavar-abortion-midwife%3A1896735&ch=Comment+is+free&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Abortion+%28News%29%2CIreland+%28News%29%2CCatholicism+%28News%29%2CHealth+%28Society%29%2CWomen+and+women%27s+interests%2CWorld+news%2CEurope+%28News%29%2CReligion+%28News%29%2CLaw&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CWomen%2CHealth+Society&c6=Emer+O%27Toole&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+07%3A15&c8=1896735&c9=Blog&c10=Comment&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=Comment+is+free&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=The+midwife+who+told+the+truth+in+the+Savita+Halappanavar+abortion+case&c66=Comment+is+free&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FComment+is+free%2FComment+is+free%2Fblog%2FComment+is+free\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Ann Maria Burke acknowledged the logic behind denying an abortion to Halappanavar: Ireland is a Catholic country</p><p>The inquest into Savita Halappanavar's death has unanimously delivered its verdict: her death was <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/savita-halappanavar-medical-misadventure-inquest\" title=\"\">due to medical misadventure</a>. Halappanavar died after being denied an emergency termination in October and her case has since been at the centre of Ireland's abortion wars. The inquest jury strongly endorsed the nine recommendations of the coroner, Ciaran MacLoughlin, including a suggestion that the Irish Medical Council lay out exactly when a doctor can intervene to save the life of a mother in similar circumstances.</p><p>The significance of this will only be known when the medical council delivers its guidelines. Abortion in Ireland is permitted where there is a real and substantial threat to the life of the mother. If the medical council agrees that termination is permitted whenever a foetal membrane ruptures, then there is an implication that a small risk to the life of the mother trumps the right to life of the foetus. Not all women with ruptured membranes develop sepsis, and, to the best of my understanding, most sepsis is treatable through antibiotics. It would, therefore, be difficult to categorise ruptured membranes as a substantial risk to life.</p><p>If the medical council agrees that termination is permitted where the foetus is unviable, then this may open the door to termination for fatal foetal abnormality, currently illegal in the Republic. But all this is simply speculation – the medical council is a conservative beast: it could equally provide guidelines that support the actions of Halappanavar's medical team, who moved to terminate only when her sepsis was genuinely life-threatening.</p><p>Halappanavar's death made people who usually ignore the fact that Ireland is a little dot of backwardness in a sea of progressive reproductive values sit up and take note. She did not die for want of a termination in a developing country, but in 21st-century western Europe. Increasingly cosmopolitan, and, in spite of the crash, no longer the EU's poor and pitiable ward, it's easy to forget that Ireland is a very conservative country compared with its European counterparts. As I <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/belief/2013/mar/15/abortion-ireland-opus-dei-catholic\" title=\"\">have argued before</a>, the separation of church and state in Ireland is an incomplete project at best.</p><p>At the inquest, Halappanavar's consultant, Dr Katherine Astbury, said that she met her patient's request for an abortion with the explanation that a poor foetal prognosis does not provide legal grounds for termination in the Republic. It must seem incomprehensible to people outside Ireland that when Halappanavar asked for a termination knowing that her pregnancy could not survive she was denied one because of the presence of a foetal heartbeat. In Ireland, however, women told that they are carrying live foetuses with fatal abnormalities routinely go to the UK to abort rather than wait weeks for their pregnancy to die, all the while growing bigger and trying to answer cheerful questions about the new baby without breaking into tears.</p><p>What's important to note here is that Halappanavar – a foreign national and a medical professional – felt it within her right to ask for a termination. Would an Irishwoman, brought up in a culture in which abortion is a dirty word and a shameful deed – and especially a less educated or differently educated Irishwoman – even have asked? Sometimes it takes an outside element to show how utterly messed up the system is.</p><p>One of the reasons that Halappanavar's death became an international news story was her husband Praveen's insistence that hospital staff told his wife that she couldn't have a termination because Ireland is a Catholic country. During the inquest, the midwife Ann Maria Burke came forward to <a href=\"http://www.irishtimes.com/news/ann-maria-burke-says-remark-was-intended-to-be-broad-and-explanatory-1.1356387\" title=\"\">apologetically explain that she was the source of this remark</a>. She said that she had only wanted to throw light on Irish culture for Halappanavar, explaining: \"It was the law of the land and there were two referendums where the Catholic church was pressing the buttons.\" From reportage, it looks as though she was all but slapped on the wrist by the coroner, who told her that Irish public hospitals do not follow any religious tenet or dogma.</p><p>Burke deserves praise, not sanction, for telling Halappanavar the truth as to why she couldn't have a termination. Where Astbury defends her medical practice through reference to law, and MacLoughlin places Irish hospitals above religious dogma, Burke alone acknowledges the logic behind the legality. The only possible logic for denying Halappanavar the treatment she would have received in other developed countries is Catholic logic.</p><p>The evidence given at the inquest shows unequivocally that Halappanavar would have received different treatment in a different jurisdiction. Astbury admitted as much, and expert witness Dr Peter Boylan has said Halappanavar would most likely be alive if she'd been given a termination, as she requested, within two days of admission to hospital.</p><p>The inquest into Halappanavar's death has delivered its verdict on what would have been her fifth wedding anniversary. I inject this element of humanity into my article not to tug on heartstrings for a pro-choice cause, but to remind us that, for all that Halappanavar's death has come to symbolise in Ireland, hers is a human story and a human tragedy. Praveen Halappanavar <a href=\"http://www.irishtimes.com/news/husband-objects-to-inquiry-members-1.554117\" title=\"\">has said</a>: \"The law has to change. Maybe Savita was born to change the law here.\" Maybe she was, but I wish that the Irish people could have done that work without her, and I wish Savita Halappanavar were celebrating her anniversary with her husband tonight.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/abortion\">Abortion</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/ireland\">Ireland</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/catholicism\">Catholicism</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/health\">Health</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/women\">Women</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/europe-news\">Europe</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/religion\">Religion</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/emer-o-toole\">Emer O'Toole</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Abortion") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Ireland") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Catholicism") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/society")) "Health") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Women") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Europe") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Religion") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law")) "Law") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Comment") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 18:15:01 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2013/apr/19/savita-halappanavar-abortion-midwife") (dc:creator nil "Emer O'Toole") (dc:subject nil "Comment is free") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T18:15:01Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407540741") (media:keywords nil "Abortion, Ireland, Catholicism, Health, Women, World news, Europe, Religion, Law") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366393819888/Ann-Maria-Burke-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Niall Carson/PA") (media:description nil "'Ann Maria Burke deserves praise, not sanction, for telling Halappanavar the truth as to why she couldn't have a termination.' Photograph: Niall Carson/PA")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366393827292/Ann-Maria-Burke-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Niall Carson/PA") (media:description nil "'Ann Maria Burke (above) deserves praise, not sanction, for telling Halappanavar the truth as to why she couldn’t have a termination.' Photograph: Niall Carson/PA")) (media:content ((height . "279") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "220") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366393871629/Savita-Halappanavar-001.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "The Irish Times/PA") (media:description nil "Savita Halappanavar died as a result of medical misadventure, a jury at her inquest has unanimously ruled. Photograph: The Irish Times/PA")))) ("Typist who complained about alleged late payment on Twitter faces lawsuit" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/45475?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Atypist-payment-twitter-faces-lawsuit%3A1896740&ch=Technology&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Twitter+%28Technology%29%2CLaw%2CMedia%2CInternet%2CBlogging+%28Media%29%2CTechnology%2CUK+news&c5=Unclassified%2CDigital+Media%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CMedia+Weekly%2CTechnology+Gadgets&c6=Owen+Bowcott&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+06%3A59&c8=1896740&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Typist+who+complained+about+alleged+late+payment+on+Twitter+faces+lawsuit&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FTechnology%2FTwitter\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Qatar-based businessman sues Lesley Kemp for libel over comments on Twitter in case that could cost her £150,000</p><p>A typist who complained on Twitter about what she claimed was late payment of a bill she was owed has discovered she is facing a libel battle that could cost her £150,000.</p><p>Lesley Kemp, 55, from Milton Keynes, is being sued by a Qatar-based businessman, Kirby Kearns, for comments she made on the site about her fees in an attempt to persuade his company to pay up.</p><p>Her case is the latest in a growing number of libel claims associated with the microblogging site but it could become a test case if, as her lawyer fears, Twitter is drawn into the action as the alleged publisher.</p><p>Robert Dougans, a solicitor specialising in libel who is representing Kemp on a no win, no fee basis, said Kearns was planning to take action against Twitter as well.</p><p>\"This case has got rather tortuous,\" Dougans told the Guardian. \"The claim against her is for up to £50,000 damages and a high court trial is likely to cost £100,000 plus.</p><p>\"He now wants to add Twitter as a defendant. She's not denying she made the comments. Her defence is justification and fair comment.\"</p><p>Disputed comments made on Twitter or elsewhere online are increasingly ending up in full-blown legal actions as the courts apply traditional defamation laws to the internet.</p><p>Sally Bercow, the wife of the Commons speaker, faces a high court hearing next week as part of the libel battle with Lord McAlpine over an allegedly defamatory Twitter message.</p><p>Kemp <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2311517/Typist-facing-100-000-libel-taking-Twitter-complain-150-unpaid-bill.html?ito=feeds-newsxml\" title=\"\">told the Daily Mail</a>: \"It was only a small amount of money that we argued over but because I was broke and stressed I took to Twitter and went on a bit of a rant.</p><p>\"There were a lot of emails between us before I took to Twitter. He said that I was damaging his reputation and that it was all done maliciously.</p><p>\"I am not used to freelance work and didn't understand there is a culture of late payments and it's not uncommon to have to wait months to receive your fee.\"</p><p>Neither Twitter nor the Qatar-based company run by Kearns responded to requests for comment.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/twitter\">Twitter</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/internet\">Internet</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/blogging\">Blogging</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/owenbowcott\">Owen Bowcott</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2013/apr/19/typist-payment-twitter-faces-lawsuit" (20849 34284) old 7 nil nil ((title nil "Typist who complained about alleged late payment on Twitter faces lawsuit") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2013/apr/19/typist-payment-twitter-faces-lawsuit") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/45475?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Atypist-payment-twitter-faces-lawsuit%3A1896740&ch=Technology&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Twitter+%28Technology%29%2CLaw%2CMedia%2CInternet%2CBlogging+%28Media%29%2CTechnology%2CUK+news&c5=Unclassified%2CDigital+Media%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CMedia+Weekly%2CTechnology+Gadgets&c6=Owen+Bowcott&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+06%3A59&c8=1896740&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Typist+who+complained+about+alleged+late+payment+on+Twitter+faces+lawsuit&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FTechnology%2FTwitter\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Qatar-based businessman sues Lesley Kemp for libel over comments on Twitter in case that could cost her £150,000</p><p>A typist who complained on Twitter about what she claimed was late payment of a bill she was owed has discovered she is facing a libel battle that could cost her £150,000.</p><p>Lesley Kemp, 55, from Milton Keynes, is being sued by a Qatar-based businessman, Kirby Kearns, for comments she made on the site about her fees in an attempt to persuade his company to pay up.</p><p>Her case is the latest in a growing number of libel claims associated with the microblogging site but it could become a test case if, as her lawyer fears, Twitter is drawn into the action as the alleged publisher.</p><p>Robert Dougans, a solicitor specialising in libel who is representing Kemp on a no win, no fee basis, said Kearns was planning to take action against Twitter as well.</p><p>\"This case has got rather tortuous,\" Dougans told the Guardian. \"The claim against her is for up to £50,000 damages and a high court trial is likely to cost £100,000 plus.</p><p>\"He now wants to add Twitter as a defendant. She's not denying she made the comments. Her defence is justification and fair comment.\"</p><p>Disputed comments made on Twitter or elsewhere online are increasingly ending up in full-blown legal actions as the courts apply traditional defamation laws to the internet.</p><p>Sally Bercow, the wife of the Commons speaker, faces a high court hearing next week as part of the libel battle with Lord McAlpine over an allegedly defamatory Twitter message.</p><p>Kemp <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2311517/Typist-facing-100-000-libel-taking-Twitter-complain-150-unpaid-bill.html?ito=feeds-newsxml\" title=\"\">told the Daily Mail</a>: \"It was only a small amount of money that we argued over but because I was broke and stressed I took to Twitter and went on a bit of a rant.</p><p>\"There were a lot of emails between us before I took to Twitter. He said that I was damaging his reputation and that it was all done maliciously.</p><p>\"I am not used to freelance work and didn't understand there is a culture of late payments and it's not uncommon to have to wait months to receive your fee.\"</p><p>Neither Twitter nor the Qatar-based company run by Kearns responded to requests for comment.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/twitter\">Twitter</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/internet\">Internet</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/blogging\">Blogging</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/owenbowcott\">Owen Bowcott</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology")) "Twitter") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law")) "Law") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Media") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology")) "Internet") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Blogging") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology")) "Technology") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk")) "UK news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 17:59:08 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2013/apr/19/typist-payment-twitter-faces-lawsuit") (dc:creator nil "Owen Bowcott") (dc:subject nil "Technology") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T17:59:08Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407541188") (media:keywords nil "Twitter, Law, Media, Internet, Blogging, Technology, UK news") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366394150595/Twitter-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "M4OS Photos/Alamy") (media:description nil "Businessman Kirby Kearns also plans to take action against Twitter, according to Lesley Kemp's lawyer. Photograph: M4OS Photos/Alamy")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366394156642/Twitter-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "M4OS Photos/Alamy") (media:description nil "Businessman Kirby Kearns also plans to take action against Twitter, according to Lesley Kemp's lawyer. Photograph: M4OS Photos/Alamy")))) ("Lawyers to miss court hearings in protest over changes to contracts" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/1767?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Alawyers-court-protest-changes-contracts%3A1896775&ch=Law&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Barristers+%28UK+only%29%2CSolicitors+%28UK+only%29%2CLaw%2CJudiciary+judges%2CUK+news&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Owen+Bowcott&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+07%3A50&c8=1896775&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Lawyers+to+miss+court+hearings+in+protest+over+changes+to+contracts&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FLaw%2FBarristers\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">CPS issues warning to lawyers taking part in all-day meeting in protest over introduction of competitive tendering</p><p>A senior judge and the Crown Prosecution Service have warned lawyers in northern England over plans for a disruptive, all-day meeting on Monday in protest at changes to legal contracts.</p><p>Barristers on the northern circuit, which takes in Manchester and Liverpool, have voted in a secret ballot to refuse work under the new Quality Assurance Scheme for Advocates (QASA).</p><p>Proposals unveiled by the Ministry of Justice this month to introduce competitive tendering for contracts to represent defendants, the removal of suspects' right to choose their lawyer and cumulative cuts in legal aid have added to the anger among both barristers and solicitors.</p><p>The letter sent out by the CPS to the heads of chambers in the north says: \"We understand the presiding judge for the northern circuit, Mr Justice Holroyde, has written to Richard Pratt QC, the circuit leader, to explain that the meeting does not provide a sufficiently good reason for court hearings not to proceed.</p><p>\"It is also our view that a meeting of barristers does not provide good cause for the usual work of prosecution to be disrupted.\"</p><p>The letter from the judiciary declares: \"We have been made aware that members of the bar and solicitors have said that they may not attend court on Monday.</p><p>\"The position of the judiciary is straightforward. It is constitutionally independent. It will hear any applications to adjourn, taking into account the interests of both parties and the administration of justice, but will only remove a case from the list if an application is made on properly arguable grounds.</p><p>\"If no application is made or if it is refused, the court hearing will proceed on Monday as listed. In recognition of the uncertainty, the court will take steps to minimise any adverse impact on witnesses who have already been warned to attend on Monday.\"</p><p>Rick Pratt QC told the Solicitors Journal earlier this month: \"We are not opposed to the principle of quality assurance. We welcome regulation which makes quality of advocacy the determining factor as to who should appear in court and at what level of case.</p><p>\"But the current scheme does not achieve that aim. It rewards competence, not excellence. It will mean that the lowest common denominator becomes the norm rather than the very high standards which we have always valued.\"</p><p>On Friday, afternoon judges on the northern circuit were hearing applications for cases to be adjourned on Monday. A number, it is known, were turned down.</p><p>A Ministry of Justice spokesman said: \"It would be disappointing if some lawyers were to choose to disrupt court schedules – this would not help them and simply inconveniences the court, the public and their clients. HM Courts & Tribunal Service will work with others across the criminal justice system to keep disruption to a minimum.</p><p>\"At this stage the government is consulting on proposals to reform legal aid in criminal law, to increase public confidence and encourage efficiency. We encourage lawyers to talk to us about the plans and respond to the consultation, rather than taking disruptive action.\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/barristers\">Barristers</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/solicitors\">Solicitors</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/judiciary\">Judiciary</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/owenbowcott\">Owen Bowcott</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/2013/apr/19/lawyers-court-protest-changes-contracts" (20849 37382) old 5 nil nil ((title nil "Lawyers to miss court hearings in protest over changes to contracts") (link nil "http://www.guar